metadata.name: Classic Automaton #36
metadata.description:
This is classical Automaton for those who loves "automaton" [cellular automata algorithm] as it is. Black and white  representation of standard algorithm organized in "Classic Automaton" canvas based on selected rules and is "framed" in Automaton variation of rules in same time.

The basic proportion of result artwork is related to square, 2 squares and 0.5 squares as a tribute to the system of "double square" proportion scale.

- "Tap" or "Mouse Click" on screen to rebuild variation;
- Press "s" key on the keyboard to save generated result in maximum resolution possible 4096 or 8192 px depends on iteration`s proportion of the result canvas to lossless PNG image file.

*use the browser`s functionality to zoom and pan the canvas.

metadata.name: Warped #78
metadata.description:
A free little toy.  Play with it and it might make art!  This is my second project using a shader.  It starts by making a simple drawing, then the shader uses noise to warp the image.  I'm making it free because 1) You really have to work at it to make art (but I think it's a lot of fun to tinker with!), and 2) the capture sometimes has minor variances from the final image - couldn't figure it out.  Made with p5js and uses some Perlin noise code by Inigo Quilez.  

After opening, press "s" to save a large jpg.

metadata.name: Flux Mesh #1
metadata.description:
This is my take on 3D simplex noise. Time is a dimension here.

Square size and color are determined by noise value over time.

Each NFT iteration has randomized color scheme, grid size, and noise zoom.

metadata.name: DiRex #10
metadata.description: Once upon a time, in a bygone era when the Earth was adorned with lush green forests and meandering rivers, dinosaurs reigned over this wondrous creation with grace and magnificence. However, the integrity of that world came to an end, and a dark and merciless age ascended upon the land. The dinosaurs, in the face of unknown forces that swept them towards oblivion, surrendered and left an indelible mark in the annals of history.

metadata.name: filaments #211
metadata.description:
A simulation using differential growth, imitating simple life-forms resembling bacteria.
The points in each filament attract and repel each other, to form doodle-like shapes in the end.

metadata.name: Adjacent #88
metadata.description:
Adjacent is the third in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art. This piece focuses on the study of Diagonal White, a series he developed between 1970 and 1975.

In 1976, Ruth Leavitt published a collection of papers titled "Artist & Computer", which highlighted the 35 prominent generative artists and asked them to discuss their work. They were posed questions like, "Do you feel art work created with a computer has now or will have an impact on art as a whole in the future?". Edward Zajec was a subject of one of those papers and in it detailed the approach to Diagonal White. 

The original program was run on a CDC 6200 computer at The Univeresiry of Trieste. The programming was done in collaboration with Dr. Matjaz Hmeljak, his long-time technical partner. Inspired by his collaborative relationship, Adjacent the output of a partnership between Christine Hall and Chris Maddern.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @christine_hall and @chrismaddern
